36. Sacrantentorum.] ‘Sacramentum' was the soldier’s oath which he swore by the ‘signa' (standards), promising fidelity to his country and his commender. The oath was administered on cnlistment. It is used here for military service, and is put in the plural number like ‘stipendia' which means ‘campaigns,' that is properly the number of times a soldier has earned pay. So ‘sacramenta’ would be the num- ber of times he has taken the cath, which as long as he remaiued with the army would ordinarily be only once, though thero were cases in which it was repeated.
